===Etymology===
From {{OF.}} ''[[armée]]'' (French ''[[armée]]''), from Proto-Romance ''[[armata]]'', a noun taken from the past participle of {{L.}} ''[[armare]]'' ‘to [[arm]]’.

===Pronunciation===
*[[w:IPA|IPA]]: British /ˈɑːmi/, American /ˈɑɹ.mi/
*[[w:SAMPA|SAMPA]]: /"A:(r)mi/
*{{audio|en-us-army.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɑː(r)mi|-ɑː(r)mi]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun|armies}}

# A large, highly organized military force concerned mainly with ground operations
#: ''The '''army''' was sent in to quell the uprising.''
# The governmental agency in charge of the nation's army.
#: ''The '''army''' opposed the legislature's involvement.''
# Any large group of people or sometimes animals working toward the same purpose.
#: ''It took an '''army''' of accountants to uncover the fraud.''
#: ''Our house is being attacked by an '''army''' of ants.''

